%N A393498 Triangle T(n,k) read by rows for n >= 4 and 2 <= k <= n-2, where T(n,k) is the number of n-digit primes p that can be written as the concatenation of a k-digit prime p1 and another prime p2, with the additional constraint that p, p1, and p2 all use exactly the same set of digits.
%C A393498 The prime p2 cannot include leading zeros, for example, 10909001 = (109)(09001) is not considered a valid concatenation even though 9001 is prime.
%H A393498 Carlos Rivera, <a href="https://primepuzzles.net/puzzles/puzz_1258.htm">Puzzle 1258. 42312143</a>.
%e A393498 5-digit primes p that can be written as the concatenation of a 2-digit prime p1 and another prime p2, such that p, p1, and p2 all use exactly the same set of digits: 13313, 13331, 19919, 19991, 37337, 53353, 79997, 83383. So T(5,2) = 8.
%e A393498 5-digit primes p that can be written as the concatenation of a 3-digit prime p1 and another prime p2, such that p, p1, and p2 all use exactly the same set of digits: 19919, 33113, 33773, 35353, 37337, 66161, 99119. So T(5,3) = 7.
%e A393498 The upper‑left triangular region begins at T(4,2) and extends as follows:
%e A393498 n\k:    2    3    4     5    6    7
%e A393498   4:    0;
%e A393498   5:    8,   7;
%e A393498   6:    6,  51,    4;
%e A393498   7:   21, 116,   95,   18;
%e A393498   8:    9, 163,  768,   151,  10;
%e A393498   9:   25, 662, 2317,  2373, 643, 30;
%e A393498   ...
%Y A393498 Cf. A000040, A105184.
